edu.jsu.mcis

Class ArgumentParser

  • java.lang.Object
    • edu.jsu.mcis.ArgumentParser

  • public class ArgumentParser
extends java.lang.Object
    This class parses an object (argument) and stores the value for user purposes

    Argument parser can store the name of the program the user wants to implement and the description of that program.

    For example, this code allows the user to add the program name and program description. 

    
ArgumentParser ap = new ArgumentParser();
 ap.addProgramName("This is the program name.");
 ap.addProgramDescription("This is the program description.");


    The program name and program description will be part of the help message and error messages printed to the command line.



    ArgumentParser provides a way of storing arguments with different values. For example, this code allows the user to add a positional argument with a name length, data type float, and description which will take a value from the command line. It also allows the user to add a named argument with a name type, default value box, data type String, and description which will take arguments from the command line if --type is called.



    
ap.addPositionalArgument(new PositionalArgument("length", Argument.ArgType.FLOAT, "This is a description"));
 ap.addNamedArgument(new NamedArgument("type", "box", Argument.ArgType.String, "This is a description."));


    ArgumentParser can check the type of Object (such as String, integer, float, boolean). It can also implement value sets that specify a discrete set of values for each argument. When it parses the arguments from the command line, each argument attribute will be checked and an appropriate exception will be thrown. For example, this code shows how to parse arguments from the command line and print the appropriate error messages.



    
try{
        ap.parse(args);
}
catch(Exception e){
        System.out.println(e.getMessage());
}

    In the above code, args is the String[] args pulled from the command line when the program runs.

    ArgumentParser can also read in information about the program and specific arguments from an XML file. For example, the following code shows how to read information from an XML file and store it in a new ArgumentParser object. 



    
try{
        ArgumentParser ap = XMLReader.readXMLFile("filePath");
}
catch(Exception e){
        System.out.println(e.getMessage());
}

    ArgumentParser can also store any information in an XML file. The following code show this.



    
ap.writeToXMLFile("filePath");

      • parse

        public void parse(java.lang.String[] args)
           throws HelpException,
                  IncorrectNumberOfArgsException,
                  IncorrectArgTypeException,
                  ArgumentDoesNotExistException,
                  IncorrectArgumentValueException
        Parses input data from the command line and throws the correct exceptions if tinput data is an incorrect format
        Parameters:
        args - the input data from the command line
        Throws:
        HelpException - if the help argument is given in the input data
        IncorrectNumberOfArgsException - if an incorrect number of positional arguments is given in the input data
        IncorrectArgTypeException - if an input argument is given as the wrong dataType specified by the user
        ArgumentDoesNotExistException - if a named argument is given in the input data that has not been created by the user
        IncorrectArgumentValueException - if the input data is not a possible value for a specified argument

      • writeToXMLFile

        public void writeToXMLFile(java.lang.String fileName)
        Writes argument parser information to the specified XML file. The program name, program description, positional arguments, and named arguments are saved in the file in standard XML format. It also saves each aspect of the arguments such as argument name, description, dataType, defaultValue, and possible value set.
        Parameters:
        fileName - the XML file to which all information will be written
